    <h2>State Unemployment Insurance (SUI) Tax Rates 2024</h2>
    <p class="section-description">The following table shows the 2024 SUI tax rates and wage bases for merit-rated employers:</p>
    
    <div class="table-wrapper">
      <table>
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th>State</th>
            <th>Wage Base</th>
            <th>Rate Range</th>
            <th>New Employer Rate</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          {taxRates.map(rate => (
            <tr>
              <td>{rate.state}</td>
              <td>{rate.wageBase}</td>
              <td>{rate.rateRange}</td>
              <td>{rate.newEmployerRate}</td>
            </tr>
          ))}
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>

    <div class="additional-notes">
      <h3>Additional Notes</h3>
      <ol>
        <li>The wage base is the maximum amount of wages per employee that are subject to unemployment tax.</li>
        <li>Rate ranges show the minimum and maximum rates that employers may pay based on their experience rating.</li>
        <li>New employer rates apply to businesses without sufficient history to qualify for an experience rating.</li>
        <li>Some states have additional assessments or surcharges that may apply.</li>
        <li>Several states have announced significant changes for 2024, including Connecticut's wage base increase from $15,000 to $25,000.</li>
      </ol>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

